00:12:15.301 --> 00:12:17.937
There were some new mills
that would come along.

00:12:17.937 --> 00:12:19.772
I actually spent ten years
working in the corrugated

00:12:19.772 --> 00:12:21.807
packaging industry
before coming to Bloomberg

00:12:21.807 --> 00:12:25.111
and worked for one of those integrated
companies who has their own paper mills.

00:12:25.678 --> 00:12:28.814
The mills that I worked for
were 100% recycled.

00:12:29.348 --> 00:12:33.619
And so some of their investment,
would have shown up in that last 20 years.

00:12:33.619 --> 00:12:34.620
They were actually

00:12:34.620 --> 00:12:37.556
they've built many of the most recent
mills over the last 20 years.

00:12:38.858 --> 00:12:39.725
But we really saw an

00:12:39.725 --> 00:12:42.728
explosion of growth
right around the time of the pandemic.

00:12:42.728 --> 00:12:48.200
So in 2023, 2.5 million
tons of new, 100% recycled

00:12:48.267 --> 00:12:52.004
containerboard
making capacity came online.

00:12:52.004 --> 00:12:54.240
And now containerboard is a technical
term.

00:12:54.240 --> 00:12:57.443
It's the big term
for the paper that goes in these boxes.

00:12:57.810 --> 00:13:01.347
So containerboard means liner board
and we're the medium.

00:13:01.714 --> 00:13:02.915
So it's this big term.

00:13:02.915 --> 00:13:07.653
So everyone's shipping flour for their
like sour dough or something

00:13:07.653 --> 00:13:12.057
during the pandemic or buying new ovens
to remodel their houses while they can.

00:13:12.491 --> 00:13:17.196
Just going back to the idea of the box
as a macroeconomic indicator.

00:13:17.196 --> 00:13:20.833
I mean, I do see people talking about
like,

00:13:20.833 --> 00:13:24.136
this idea of boxes as a leading indicator
every once in a while.

00:13:24.136 --> 00:13:27.139
It is unconventional,
but some people do it.

00:13:27.173 --> 00:13:31.210
How valuable are box shipments
or tracking the box

00:13:31.210 --> 00:13:34.680
industry in terms of trying to figure out
what's going on with the consumer?

00:13:35.181 --> 00:13:37.216
Very important for the consumer.

00:13:37.216 --> 00:13:41.287
Like I said, about 50% of box consumption
is going to go through a grocery store.

00:13:42.087 --> 00:13:45.090
So when you start to see box
shipments slip,

00:13:45.591 --> 00:13:49.695
we probably need to be looking at
grocery stores and CPG companies,

00:13:50.696 --> 00:13:52.131
to see what's going on there.

00:13:52.131 --> 00:13:55.134
And we have seen a very

00:13:55.601 --> 00:13:58.604
challenged consumer environment
over the last two years.

00:13:58.938 --> 00:14:02.041
My personal opinion, I would say
we're in a consumer goods recession

00:14:02.308 --> 00:14:04.176
because of what we've seen.

00:14:04.176 --> 00:14:07.546
First half of 2025,
box shipments were down 12%

00:14:07.546 --> 00:14:09.248
from the height of the pandemic.

00:14:09.248 --> 00:14:10.983
That's a massive fall off.

00:14:10.983 --> 00:14:12.218
So earlier

00:14:12.218 --> 00:14:15.221
we talked about how we would measure
these things in billions of square feet.

00:14:16.222 --> 00:14:21.193
Well, in 2021, we had 416,000,000,000ft².

00:14:21.994 --> 00:14:24.363
The first half was right around
half of that.

00:14:24.363 --> 00:14:27.366
So like about 208. Yeah.

00:14:27.800 --> 00:14:30.803
It was really bad.

00:14:31.570 --> 00:14:32.204
Quick math

00:14:32.204 --> 00:14:36.041
with 190,000,000,000ft²
for the first half of 2025.

00:14:36.475 --> 00:14:38.377
So pretty big fall off.

00:14:38.377 --> 00:14:41.614
What's happening with prices
and so obviously right.

00:14:41.614 --> 00:14:44.350
So measuring square feet is one thing.

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:47.453
What is happening with prices.

00:14:47.553 --> 00:14:50.623
Well, the pricing
the pricing discussion is one that,

00:14:51.123 --> 00:14:53.626
is sure full of controversy.

00:14:53.626 --> 00:14:57.363
So what drives pricing is it
is it truly supply and demand?

00:14:57.363 --> 00:15:00.099
Is it something that's more cost based?

00:15:00.099 --> 00:15:01.634
For many, many years in the US,

00:15:01.634 --> 00:15:05.204
it was supply demand based
where mill operating rates would hit

00:15:05.371 --> 00:15:09.174
96%, inventories would get real low
and they would raise prices.

00:15:09.541 --> 00:15:12.711
Or the opposite mill operators would go
below 90%,

00:15:12.978 --> 00:15:15.381
inventories would rise
and prices would fall.

00:15:15.381 --> 00:15:16.081
But over the last year

00:15:16.081 --> 00:15:19.385
and a half, we've actually seen
none of those fundamentals hold up.

00:15:19.952 --> 00:15:22.621
So mill operating rates
have barely been 90%.

00:15:22.621 --> 00:15:25.057
Inventories hit five weeks
at the end of the first quarter.

00:15:25.057 --> 00:15:27.626
And yet prices still went up.
Five weeks is a lot of it.

00:15:27.626 --> 00:15:29.461
Five weeks is a lot of inventory.

00:15:29.461 --> 00:15:31.830
Historical averages are around four weeks.

00:15:32.965 --> 00:15:34.533
To to kind of set the

00:15:34.533 --> 00:15:38.370
floor there three and a half weeks
gets a little dangerous.

00:15:38.370 --> 00:15:39.405
When it's a little lighter than that.

00:15:39.405 --> 00:15:42.207
We start worrying
about supply chain issues.

00:15:42.207 --> 00:15:44.944
About half of the the containerboard,

00:15:44.944 --> 00:15:48.747
is made at a paper mill
and shipped by rail to a box plant.

00:15:49.181 --> 00:15:52.484
And rail isn't quite as fast and efficient

00:15:52.484 --> 00:15:55.487
as an LTL,
or will actually be a full truckload.

00:15:56.055 --> 00:15:59.558
But you can carry more rolls by rail
than you can by a truck.

00:15:59.758 --> 00:16:02.761
So you kind of have to have a little bit
more of that time,

00:16:03.028 --> 00:16:05.431
to allow for the transit for those roles.

00:16:05.431 --> 00:16:10.269
What's your take on why paper companies
are actually increasing prices, even,

00:16:10.269 --> 00:16:13.472
you know, when inventory seems to be high
and demand is going down.

00:16:13.472 --> 00:16:14.573
Well, it's funny you ask that.

00:16:14.573 --> 00:16:17.443
So four years ago,
I started trying to figure out

00:16:17.443 --> 00:16:20.446
if we could read the tea leaves,
sort of say.

00:16:20.512 --> 00:16:23.282
And, we put together a mix of inputs.

00:16:23.282 --> 00:16:26.618
And having worked in the industry,
we kind of know how the sausage is made.

00:16:27.252 --> 00:16:30.456
And what we did was
we put together this series of inputs

00:16:30.456 --> 00:16:33.459
and we correlated it
back to historic movements.

00:16:33.926 --> 00:16:39.298
And our algorithm explains
93% of the reasons why prices have moved

00:16:39.898 --> 00:16:43.202
for Bloomberg
terminal class A box pricing algo.

00:16:43.302 --> 00:16:43.702
Yeah.

00:16:43.702 --> 00:16:47.172
So BK, BCI I index for people
who are on the terminal.

00:16:47.873 --> 00:16:50.242
Yeah. Pull this up right I c keep going.

00:16:50.242 --> 00:16:51.810
Well bk b

00:16:53.178 --> 00:16:54.680
wait, what is it BCI yeah.

00:16:54.680 --> 00:16:58.183
Do you see BCI stands for Bloomberg
corrugated box cost index.

00:16:58.851 --> 00:17:02.554
And up until this year, when we did our

00:17:02.788 --> 00:17:07.359
the last multiple regression analysis,
it had a 93% r-square.

00:17:07.359 --> 00:17:10.362
So it was really good, right.

00:17:10.562 --> 00:17:15.501
Well, pricing in the industry
diverted from our index this year

00:17:15.501 --> 00:17:19.705
where prices went up
even though costs are going down.

00:17:19.705 --> 00:17:23.042
And that's actually
not a complete anomaly.

00:17:23.042 --> 00:17:27.112
We did see this in our index
a few years back in 2017, 2018.

00:17:27.713 --> 00:17:29.281
But it wasn't quite as pronounced.

00:17:29.281 --> 00:17:29.882
Oh, sorry.

00:17:29.882 --> 00:17:32.551
Just to be clear,
because I want to get this right.

00:17:32.551 --> 00:17:35.788
And the index that I'm looking at
is the box cost index.

00:17:35.788 --> 00:17:41.193
So it's not so much that it's
measuring the cost of box like, so box

00:17:41.193 --> 00:17:44.196
prices can go up even though this line on
the chart is rolling.

00:17:44.196 --> 00:17:46.198
Correct. This is important. Yeah.

00:17:46.198 --> 00:17:50.335
And some might call this,
kind of organic margin expansion.

00:17:51.236 --> 00:17:54.506
Others have more colorful words for it.

00:17:54.807 --> 00:17:59.044
But in the US, 90% of
the industry is vertically integrated.

00:17:59.044 --> 00:18:01.447
And what that means is
they have their own paper mills.

00:18:01.447 --> 00:18:05.851
They move that paper to their own box
plants and sell it to their own customers.

00:18:06.218 --> 00:18:10.189
And so there really isn't much of an open
market the way there is in other regions.

00:18:10.589 --> 00:18:12.491
In other regions, like in Europe,

00:18:12.491 --> 00:18:14.793
they don't have that
vertical integration level.

00:18:14.793 --> 00:18:18.330
So there is a much more robust
open market, and it drives

00:18:18.330 --> 00:18:21.333
prices down because of normal supply
demand fundamentals.

00:18:21.333 --> 00:18:25.704
If you do have just an absolute glut of
inventory, prices are going to fall.

00:18:26.438 --> 00:18:29.441
Our best data says globally,

00:18:29.441 --> 00:18:33.612
we have around 50 million
tons of oversupply of containerboard.

00:18:34.713 --> 00:18:36.815
Now we don't have that just in the US.

00:18:36.815 --> 00:18:40.252
That's a global number,
but that does kind of

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:43.388
alter your frame of consciousness.

