space to, good ratio,

00:25:36.968 --> 00:25:39.037
but then that would have taken up
more warehouse space

00:25:39.037 --> 00:25:40.705
and made that whole process
less efficient.

00:25:40.705 --> 00:25:43.975
So try all kinds of algorithms
that I'm not even thinking

00:25:43.975 --> 00:25:45.277
about as the end consumer here.

00:25:45.277 --> 00:25:46.778
There are lots of algorithms.

00:25:46.778 --> 00:25:50.382
And when you think about boxes
and packaging in traditional e-commerce,

00:25:50.549 --> 00:25:54.986
they are looking to optimize
not just from a packaging standpoint,

00:25:54.986 --> 00:25:58.290
from like from a pricing position, but

00:25:58.723 --> 00:26:01.626
really from a cube
in the shipments. Right?

00:26:01.626 --> 00:26:05.397
So we have to think that Amazon
is going to process all these orders

00:26:05.597 --> 00:26:08.800
or chewy or whatever
the e-commerce platform is.

00:26:09.434 --> 00:26:13.271
They process the orders, they're going
to go through their distribution centers.

00:26:13.271 --> 00:26:15.040
And if you're Amazon,
you have your own trucks.

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:16.107
You want to make sure that you can put

00:26:16.107 --> 00:26:18.076
as many of those things
on a truck as possible.

00:26:18.076 --> 00:26:19.911
There's all kinds of different points

00:26:19.911 --> 00:26:23.281
at which the optimization could occur
for including packing the truck.

00:26:23.915 --> 00:26:25.550
You know, when we're talking about broader

00:26:25.550 --> 00:26:28.553
macroeconomic data
these days, in particular,

00:26:28.820 --> 00:26:32.424
there are a lot of questions
about the degree to which the aggregates

00:26:32.424 --> 00:26:32.791
are missing

00:26:32.791 --> 00:26:36.728
part of the story, and specifically
in a lot of commerce these days, anytime

00:26:36.995 --> 00:26:39.998
there's some retail CEO
that like things are holding up well,

00:26:40.131 --> 00:26:42.567
but it's really being driven
by the high end.

00:26:42.567 --> 00:26:44.102
The high end is keeping it afloat.

00:26:44.102 --> 00:26:47.105
The middle consumer is getting squeezed,
lower income is getting squeezed.

00:26:47.105 --> 00:26:49.741
You know, all kinds of things
are there different.

00:26:49.741 --> 00:26:51.643
You know, we're talking in aggregate
when you

00:26:51.643 --> 00:26:54.646
when you talk about box square footage
having been shipped.

00:26:54.746 --> 00:26:58.483
But is there more granular data
that one could look at in

00:26:58.483 --> 00:27:02.320
terms of the quality of cardboard, etc.,
that could tell us different things

00:27:02.320 --> 00:27:06.091
about what's strong within the economy,
even if the big numbers are declining.

00:27:06.091 --> 00:27:10.462
The fancy boxes,
the fancy box is not really there.

00:27:11.029 --> 00:27:15.367
So one of the problems that our industry
faces is that we don't have great data.

00:27:15.734 --> 00:27:19.504
Having worked in the industry
and having provided that data, it

00:27:20.472 --> 00:27:23.074
it's a chore that no one really double
checks.

00:27:23.074 --> 00:27:24.943
You've brought on a new customer, right?

00:27:24.943 --> 00:27:27.012
And you're submitting all your paperwork
for the new customer.

00:27:27.012 --> 00:27:31.349
One of those things
is a classification of their NAICs code.

00:27:31.683 --> 00:27:35.086
The North American industry could well,
no one ever checks

00:27:35.086 --> 00:27:37.022
to make sure that's proper, right?

00:27:37.022 --> 00:27:40.892
You just kind of wing it you know,
look it up and see if they've maybe

00:27:40.892 --> 00:27:43.428
filed it with the Secretary of Commerce
or something like that.

00:27:43.428 --> 00:27:45.296
And and that's it.

00:27:45.296 --> 00:27:49.801
So the the granular data is murky at best,

00:27:50.101 --> 00:27:54.272
but it is insightful and it is consistent
because there is a cost

00:27:54.305 --> 00:27:56.341
to changing your supplier.

00:27:56.341 --> 00:27:58.977
Like we we do see it happen.

00:27:58.977 --> 00:28:01.813
And for very big box customers
they don't like change.

00:28:01.813 --> 00:28:06.551
And you have a long standing relationship
typically many, many years.

00:28:06.985 --> 00:28:08.653
You have lots of SKUs.

00:28:08.653 --> 00:28:11.156
And if you're a really big company
and you have operating

00:28:11.156 --> 00:28:14.159
facilities all over the place,
you don't want to go through that.

00:28:14.459 --> 00:28:18.029
So the data, while murky,
might be consistent.

00:28:18.029 --> 00:28:21.032
And we do see some of those things,
like in 2024, for instance,

00:28:21.099 --> 00:28:24.869
we saw that manufactured food
felt like by 3.7%.

00:28:25.336 --> 00:28:27.172
So if you combine that with beverage,

00:28:27.172 --> 00:28:30.308
it was a little over of a 4% decline
in box usage.

00:28:30.975 --> 00:28:33.678
Now how do we describe that?

00:28:33.678 --> 00:28:37.248
Did did those companies
see similar falls in their volume?

00:28:38.016 --> 00:28:42.087
I think I think the data would suggest
that that's probably very close.

00:28:43.755 --> 00:28:44.255
Corrugated

00:28:44.255 --> 00:28:47.258
packaging does have some known trade offs.

00:28:47.292 --> 00:28:50.295
One of those things is a returnable
plastic container.

00:28:51.062 --> 00:28:54.332
That is mainly being pushed right now
towards produce.

00:28:54.499 --> 00:28:57.936
Walmart specifically Sprouts
market, have been pushing

00:28:57.936 --> 00:29:02.340
some of their people to adopt returnable
plastic containers as a viable option.

00:29:02.674 --> 00:29:04.175
It reduces waste.

00:29:04.175 --> 00:29:07.879
They're building supply chains around
these things to help carry them around.

00:29:08.580 --> 00:29:12.150
So that is one of the things that we've
seen kind of cut into box consumption.

00:29:12.684 --> 00:29:17.922
We don't know that it's a big thing yet,
but it is out there and it is a thing.

00:29:18.356 --> 00:29:24.195
The other thing that we've seen
is a movement to larger format boxes, some

00:29:24.195 --> 00:29:29.000
that are the size of a pallet, you know,
48in long, 40in wide and maybe 40in tall.

00:29:29.467 --> 00:29:31.336
A great playhouse for your young kids.

00:29:32.437 --> 00:29:33.872
I remember doing that with

00:29:33.872 --> 00:29:36.841
huge boxes, turning them into houses.

00:29:37.675 --> 00:29:41.479
Why would anyone invest in this space
currently?

00:29:41.479 --> 00:29:46.084
Because when you describe
this enormous glut in supply

00:29:46.351 --> 00:29:50.555
and then the fact that demand is going
down, maybe it's because of the tariffs.

00:29:50.555 --> 00:29:51.856
Maybe if the U.S.

00:29:51.856 --> 00:29:56.227
starts manufacturing more goods, it'll
domestically it'll start to pick up again.

00:29:56.928 --> 00:30:01.533
But it seems like most of the lines
are kind of trending in the wrong way.

00:30:02.100 --> 00:30:06.271
What what exactly is like
the allure of this industry?

00:30:06.571 --> 00:30:11.042
That's a great question, and I wish
I knew the answer, other than they do

00:30:11.042 --> 00:30:15.680
have dividends that they have been been
paying and and consistently paying.

00:30:15.680 --> 00:30:20.151
So, so it's considered like a fairly
like stable state, very stable dividend.

00:30:20.318 --> 00:30:21.586
I think it's a pretty safe investment.

00:30:21.586 --> 00:30:25.190
We do see I mean, it's very popular from,

00:30:25.190 --> 00:30:29.160
from a terminal standpoint, I get bluer
clients at retail all the time.

00:30:29.160 --> 00:30:32.564
They're looking to figure out
if this is still a good investment.

00:30:32.831 --> 00:30:35.834
And while we don't do buy, sell,
hold recommendations,

00:30:36.167 --> 00:30:39.170
we still see a lot of traffic
in these in these lanes.

00:30:39.237 --> 00:30:41.873
Does it just depend on
how big your company

00:30:41.873 --> 00:30:45.109
actually is and how much pricing power
you have in the market?

00:30:45.109 --> 00:30:47.011
Well, see, I think that's a myth.

00:30:47.011 --> 00:30:50.014
I think
I think there really isn't pricing power.

00:30:50.014 --> 00:30:52.217
If there were pricing power,

00:30:52.217 --> 00:30:55.220
we wouldn't see some of the actions
that we're seeing in the world today.

00:30:55.420 --> 00:31:00.491
And what I mean by that is there are some
mills that make a really robust paper.

00:31:00.692 --> 00:31:02.961
It performs really, really well.

00:31:02.961 --> 00:31:04.429
And there are scientific properties

00:31:04.429 --> 00:31:07.432
to that paper
that set it apart from anything else.

00:31:08.266 --> 00:31:10.535
And yet they aren't
getting the premium that

00:31:10.535 --> 00:31:13.805
they should be getting
because there is an alternative.

00:31:13.805 --> 00:31:14.672
And and it's

00:31:15.673 --> 00:31:18.676
it's like wanting
a Ferrari and selling for a mustang.

00:31:18.776 --> 00:31:21.613
They're both great, but one obviously has

00:31:21.613 --> 00:31:25.383
the allure
and one has its client base too.

00:31:25.383 --> 00:31:29.120
And when you can buy a mustang
and it works,

00:31:30.355 --> 00:31:32.690
you're not always going to want to buy
that Ferrari.

00:31:32.690 --> 00:31:35.693
Well, actually, this sort of gets me
to where I want to go.

00:31:35.793 --> 00:31:38.196
First of all, what what would be the name

00:31:38.196 --> 00:31:42.934
of the biggest box or packaging expo
in the United States like that?

00:31:42.934 --> 00:31:44.302
Get it together somewhere?

00:31:44.302 --> 00:31:44.669
Yeah.

00:31:44.669 --> 00:31:47.739
In in big round terms
for packaging pack expo.

00:31:47.772 --> 00:31:48.740
Where's that Vegas.

00:31:48.740 --> 00:31:51.542
That's going to be in Vegas
this year. Maybe we'll go one day.

00:31:51.542 --> 00:31:51.843
All right.

00:31:51.843 --> 00:31:54.279
So setting aside the volume
and pricing trends

00:31:54.279 --> 00:31:56.714
which we take for granted,
everyone is curious about

00:31:56.714 --> 00:32:01.653
what would be the hot topics right now
that would be discussed at Pac Expo.

00:32:01.786 --> 00:32:05.523
Ooh, sustainability
has been a really big topic

00:32:05.523 --> 00:32:08.092
for a long time, and it's matched with

00:32:09.961 --> 00:32:12.063
extended producer responsibility laws.

00:32:12.063 --> 00:32:16.467
So this is a state
by state initiative to basically shift

00:32:16.467 --> 00:32:18.069
the burden of recycling away

00:32:18.069 --> 00:32:21.639
from its residents and onto the companies
who are creating the waste.

00:32:22.340 --> 00:32:24.008
How does that work exactly?

00:32:24.008 --> 00:32:27.512
So right now, we have a handful of states
who've actually passed legislation.

00:32:27.812 --> 00:32:31.249
Oregon's the first one
that that is really kind of enacting this,

00:32:31.716 --> 00:32:33.918
and they've set up a fee schedule.

00:32:33.918 --> 00:32:38.656
They've measured how much waste their
state produces in a month or in a year,

00:32:39.257 --> 00:32:43.127
and they've allocated
a certain number of dollars

00:32:43.127 --> 00:32:46.364
per pound or cents per
pound for each one of those commodities.

00:32:46.798 --> 00:32:49.734
And if you're selling something
into the state, they are essentially

00:32:49.734 --> 00:32:53.137
placing a fee on the waste
that you're sending in their state.

00:32:53.438 --> 00:32:55.106
And you have to pay a check to them.

00:32:55.106 --> 00:32:58.376
Mike, can you talk a little bit more
about the economics of recycling?

00:32:58.376 --> 00:32:59.243
Because I put

00:33:00.211 --> 00:33:01.446
a lot of the cardboard I

00:33:01.446 --> 00:33:05.149
used into the problem, into the proper
bin, the economics, the recycling.

00:33:05.283 --> 00:33:09.854
Like, yeah, but like I'm always in
this goes with any recycling really,

00:33:09.854 --> 00:33:13.458
which is that when I think about the labor
that actually when I think about a,

00:33:13.624 --> 00:33:16.527
the degree of diligence
that people and I would say,

00:33:16.527 --> 00:33:20.398
and probably higher than average diligence
about been, proper been allocation.

00:33:20.565 --> 00:33:24.135
But I know I'm not perfect, but
when I think about the degree of diligence

00:33:24.135 --> 00:33:25.003
and the inefficiency

00:33:25.003 --> 00:33:28.940
and then the labor and all of this stuff
and then talk to a guy, what?

00:33:29.040 --> 00:33:32.744
When is it, actually economical
and when is it just sort of some sort

00:33:32.744 --> 00:33:38.449
of cargo cult type, behavior that people
engage in where there's no real purpose?

00:33:38.716 --> 00:33:41.252
Well, so most, most of the time

00:33:42.420 --> 00:33:45.423
the recycling fees are paid by taxes.

00:33:45.990 --> 00:33:48.793
My street, for instance,
that was not the case.

00:33:48.793 --> 00:33:51.329
And I had to pay $25 a quarter for a bin.

00:33:51.329 --> 00:33:54.332
Not not terrible, but I had to pay for it.

00:33:54.932 --> 00:33:58.269
The economics in big round numbers
work like this.

00:33:58.269 --> 00:34:03.775
It costs anywhere from about $400
a ton upwards to $700 a ton to go out

00:34:03.775 --> 00:34:08.780
and do the collections and processing for
recovered materials, all of that stuff.

00:34:08.780 --> 00:34:11.849
So you'll see a a truck
come and pick up your recyclables.

00:34:12.116 --> 00:34:15.620
It goes to a facility called a Murph,
a municipal recovery facility.

00:34:16.621 --> 00:34:17.855
And there it's process.

00:34:17.855 --> 00:34:20.658
And they have lots of lines
that sort things out

00:34:20.658 --> 00:34:22.927
plastics and metals and papers
and all that stuff.

00:34:22.927 --> 00:34:25.096
And then they produce bales.

00:34:25.096 --> 00:34:28.099
So a a compact

00:34:28.433 --> 00:34:31.636
cube of sorts of these materials,
and then they get sold.

00:34:32.904 --> 00:34:34.539
So if we were to

00:34:34.539 --> 00:34:39.043
just use a big round number
and say $500 a ton, the net ton that comes

00:34:39.043 --> 00:34:43.781
out of the Murph only has a street value
between 100 to $140 a ton.

00:34:44.382 --> 00:34:46.451
Very little getting that right.
That's just terrible.

00:34:46.451 --> 00:34:47.552
That's terrible.

00:34:47.552 --> 00:34:50.421
And the craziest thing is
the corrugated box.

00:34:50.421 --> 00:34:50.822
Yeah.

00:34:50.822 --> 00:34:55.293
Is what really makes household
recycling even work.

00:34:55.693 --> 00:34:58.129
Because, we know from from data.

00:34:58.129 --> 00:35:02.133
And this is something which I challenged
several years ago, our best data says

00:35:02.133 --> 00:35:06.370
that we recycle about 66% of
of the corrugated boxes in the U.S.

00:35:06.671 --> 00:35:08.406
it's a pretty good number.

00:35:08.406 --> 00:35:11.342
The industry used to say
93% of boxes got recycled.

00:35:11.342 --> 00:35:13.778
There's no way that's possible.

00:35:13.778 --> 00:35:16.914
But we don't have the data
to say it's lower than 66%.

00:35:18.549 --> 00:35:21.519
But we do have a methodology that we use
to kind of get their

00:35:21.519 --> 00:35:24.522
it was actually supported
by the National Renewable Energy Lab.

00:35:24.755 --> 00:35:27.692
Now you can probably shoot some holes
in some of their stuff too.

00:35:27.692 --> 00:35:32.563
But big point is we know that about 60
some percent of these get recycled.

00:35:32.864 --> 00:35:35.867
And we know they have a very robust
aftermarket.

00:35:35.967 --> 00:35:38.402
We process about 35 million

00:35:38.402 --> 00:35:42.273
tons of old corrugated cartons
almost every year.

00:35:42.673 --> 00:35:45.676
About a third of them
are going to go overseas.

00:35:45.943 --> 00:35:49.647
There are a lot of other countries
that want the virgin fiber that we produce

00:35:49.647 --> 00:35:51.449
here.

00:35:51.449 --> 00:35:55.052
Now that we've revealed
the depressing truth about recycling,

00:35:55.353 --> 00:35:58.189
let me ask a slightly
more positive question, which is

00:35:58.189 --> 00:36:02.426
have there been any cool technological
developments when it comes to box making?

00:36:03.594 --> 00:36:06.964
They are constantly patenting boxes,

00:36:07.565 --> 00:36:10.568
making new equipment to make them faster.

00:36:12.236 --> 00:36:14.839
Improving the the way we make the paper,

00:36:14.839 --> 00:36:17.842
we're trying to make stronger paper
that's lighter and weight.

00:36:17.975 --> 00:36:20.978
So if you think about some of these, we'll
go back to the EPR laws for a second.

00:36:22.380 --> 00:36:25.750
Those fees are based on the weight
of what you're consuming.

00:36:25.750 --> 00:36:30.254
So if the companies can buy a lighter
weight material then their fees go down.

00:36:30.388 --> 00:36:30.721
Right.

00:36:30.721 --> 00:36:34.091
So there is a push now
to see if we can lightweight the paper,

00:36:35.026 --> 00:36:37.595
make it as strong but with less weight.

00:36:37.595 --> 00:36:40.231
And so these are things that we're going
to see really take some

00:36:40.231 --> 00:36:42.567
some shape in the next 5 to 10 years.

00:36:42.567 --> 00:36:45.203
You know I'm glad you mentioned export.

00:36:45.203 --> 00:36:49.373
One of the things that I've noticed
whenever I am, traveling abroad,

00:36:49.373 --> 00:36:50.875
even to fairly rich countries,

00:36:50.875 --> 00:36:53.844
but I definitely notice it
when I'm in poorer countries,

00:36:53.844 --> 00:36:57.915
is that the quality of packaging materials
is distinctly worse than here.

00:36:57.915 --> 00:37:01.152
So and I
the the example that I often notice

00:37:01.152 --> 00:37:04.255
is, you know, you buy a bottle of water
in a U.S grocery store.

00:37:04.255 --> 00:37:08.059
It's nice, it's sturdy,
it holds its, form very well.

00:37:08.259 --> 00:37:12.597
You buy a bottle of water
at a grocery store in Guatemala

00:37:12.597 --> 00:37:15.566
where I was a couple of years ago
from Mexico. It's crinkly.

00:37:15.566 --> 00:37:17.802
It smashes over easily.

00:37:17.802 --> 00:37:20.037
You could tell that it's a less durable,

00:37:21.472 --> 00:37:22.240
plastic.

00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:26.244
If we were to look at the cardboard boxes
running through a developing economies

00:37:26.244 --> 00:37:30.281
such as, Guatemala, etc.,
we see that this is noticeably different

00:37:30.281 --> 00:37:32.250
than the quality of cardboard
that we're seeing here.

00:37:32.250 --> 00:37:33.951
The technical term is going to be furnish.

00:37:33.951 --> 00:37:34.252
Okay.

00:37:34.252 --> 00:37:37.021
So what are you using to make the boxes?

00:37:37.021 --> 00:37:41.292
The US has historically been a maker
of virgin craft liner board, meaning

00:37:41.592 --> 00:37:43.861
they cut down trees.
They chipped the trees.

00:37:43.861 --> 00:37:48.099
They they turn those chips
in into new virgin paper

00:37:48.132 --> 00:37:49.900
that's actually been declining
and reversing.

00:37:49.900 --> 00:37:52.903
We've seen more and more recycled capacity
come online.

00:37:52.903 --> 00:37:55.706
And because we've still had a very good
virgin base,

00:37:55.706 --> 00:37:58.709
the recycled paper here in the US
has been very good.

00:37:58.809 --> 00:38:01.879
Now in other countries
they may not have southern yellow pine,

00:38:02.213 --> 00:38:05.016
so they are buying rock
or they're using their own

00:38:05.016 --> 00:38:08.252
oak or oaks, old corrugated cartons.

00:38:09.287 --> 00:38:12.256
So they're they're just
going to rip up the stuff that they have.

00:38:12.256 --> 00:38:16.227
If they start with a low quality box,
then they're going to get a low quality

00:38:16.227 --> 00:38:18.229
paper on the back end and less

00:38:18.229 --> 00:38:21.565
so sometimes they are going to have
a lower grade paper.

00:38:21.966 --> 00:38:25.836
And in other areas of the world
they actually have different definitions

00:38:25.836 --> 00:38:28.773
for that kind of paper.
So they would have different grades of it.

00:38:28.773 --> 00:38:31.108
And so yeah, you
sometimes you get the low grade paper

00:38:31.108 --> 00:38:34.111
because it's a commodity
and then it'll work.

00:38:34.178 --> 00:38:36.380
So I just have one more question.

00:38:36.380 --> 00:38:38.215
Just to wrap it all up.

00:38:38.215 --> 00:38:39.750
That's a packaging joke.

00:38:39.750 --> 00:38:40.718
Packaging joke. Okay.

00:38:40.718 --> 00:38:43.788
Wrapping it all up, summarizing
what's your,

00:38:44.021 --> 00:38:47.124
prediction for the second half of the year
in terms of box shipments?

00:38:47.325 --> 00:38:49.260
We think they're still
going to be very challenged.

00:38:50.594 --> 00:38:52.463
Full year, we're saying

00:38:52.463 --> 00:38:56.300
there's probably going to be down
2.5%, maybe as high as 3%.

00:38:56.300 --> 00:38:59.303
It really depends on what happens.

00:38:59.470 --> 00:39:03.774
A lot of this is stemming from tariffs
and policy coming out of the,

00:39:04.008 --> 00:39:04.909
the white House.

00:39:04.909 --> 00:39:07.878
So it really depends on
how much confidence

00:39:07.878 --> 00:39:10.881
some of these companies have as they look
forward.

00:39:11.382 --> 00:39:15.786
We've seen the the number of containers
coming into the U.S, like the cargo ships

00:39:16.053 --> 00:39:17.488
was front loaded.

00:39:17.488 --> 00:39:17.822
Right.

00:39:17.822 --> 00:39:21.092
And then and now that the tariffs
are kind of here or maybe they're not here

00:39:21.525 --> 00:39:24.528
and they've been kind of
tapering off a bit,

00:39:25.129 --> 00:39:27.765
it will be very curious
to see what happens.

00:39:27.765 --> 00:39:30.901
But to to maybe think about it
another way.

00:39:31.268 --> 00:39:33.871
You know, most Americans buy stuff
when they have money

00:39:33.871 --> 00:39:36.240
and when they don't have money,
they put it on credit cards.

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:39.176
And we're seeing records,
amount of credit card debt.

00:39:39.176 --> 00:39:42.513
And that's not a great sign
for if people are going to spend money.

00:39:42.780 --> 00:39:45.649
So we don't really think that that's

00:39:45.649 --> 00:39:48.652
a really hot outlook
for even the for the holidays.

00:39:48.853 --> 00:39:51.322
Or Americans can spend money probably.

00:39:51.322 --> 00:39:54.325
Is it going to look exactly like it did
in prior years?

00:39:54.392 --> 00:39:55.292
Probably not.

00:39:55.292 --> 00:39:55.693
All right.

00:39:55.693 --> 00:39:59.630
Ryan Fox containers and packaging analyst
at Bloomberg Intelligence,

00:39:59.630 --> 00:40:02.133
thank you so much. Thanks for having me.

00:40:02.133 --> 00:40:05.836
You know, one thing
I really like about, Ryan and people like

00:40:05.836 --> 00:40:09.707
that is when they trot out
all the numbers off the top of their head.

00:40:09.707 --> 00:40:11.041
Yeah, that was really impressive.

00:40:11.041 --> 00:40:12.243
That was no notes.

00:40:12.243 --> 00:40:15.212
And he had answers
for pretty much everything.

00:40:15.813 --> 00:40:19.550
I wouldn't if someone had asked me
how I thought they would measure

00:40:19.550 --> 00:40:24.555
box shipments, I might have guessed,
you know, cubic feet, red square feet.

00:40:24.755 --> 00:40:28.292
But yes, I, I wouldn't have, you know,
all this covering the world stuff.

00:40:28.592 --> 00:40:30.161
Yeah. It's pretty cool. Yeah.

00:40:30.161 --> 00:40:35.065
And I guess the question over,
how useful a macroeconomic indicator

00:40:35.132 --> 00:40:38.936
boxes actually are,
it still kind of lingers because we did

00:40:38.936 --> 00:40:42.506
have retail sales data,
for the past two months that are available

00:40:42.740 --> 00:40:45.242
that came in, like, pretty resilient,
pretty strong.

00:40:45.242 --> 00:40:47.778
Despite the decline in box shipments.

00:40:47.778 --> 00:40:50.881
I what was the term huge
cart to carton commerce?

00:40:51.115 --> 00:40:53.150
I really like that
because it's true. Right.

00:40:53.150 --> 00:40:57.021
What is e-commerce that now encompasses
so many different things.

00:40:57.021 --> 00:40:59.490
So there is
this sort of classic e-commerce

00:40:59.490 --> 00:41:01.992
where you go on a website,
you buy a thing and it comes in a box.

00:41:01.992 --> 00:41:04.161
But then there's of course, you know, buy

00:41:04.161 --> 00:41:07.298
and you pick up at the store
and that's a slightly different variation.

00:41:07.298 --> 00:41:11.569
Or maybe you get, food
delivered in a cardboard box, etc..

00:41:11.702 --> 00:41:14.705
So I like the idea of,
okay, e-commerce is so broad

00:41:14.705 --> 00:41:17.775
that if we want to have like
for like trajectories of some of these

00:41:17.942 --> 00:41:21.779
use cases for cardboard boxes, we have to
maybe get a little bit more granular.

00:41:21.812 --> 00:41:23.214
Well, that reminds me, actually,

00:41:23.214 --> 00:41:26.951
I think one thing that's still really
underappreciated about the packaging

00:41:26.951 --> 00:41:30.287
industry is how much it feeds into broader
inflation.

00:41:30.621 --> 00:41:31.655
Yes, yes.

00:41:31.655 --> 00:41:34.792
And this is something I remember
some economists bringing this up,

00:41:35.259 --> 00:41:37.461
during the post pandemic era.

00:41:37.461 --> 00:41:41.699
But the interesting thing is now,
even though box shipments are going down,

00:41:41.699 --> 00:41:45.503
prices still seem to be kind of sticky
and even going up.

00:41:45.503 --> 00:41:47.538
So what does that mean for inflation?

00:41:47.538 --> 00:41:50.941
I like to think when you buy,
I always think about this and sometimes

00:41:50.941 --> 00:41:54.512
it maybe gets a little metaphysical, but
when you buy a thing in a grocery store,

00:41:54.512 --> 00:41:58.215
let's say you buy an avocado or you buy,
what?

00:41:58.382 --> 00:42:00.885
Like what are you buying
when you buy the avocado? Right.

00:42:00.885 --> 00:42:04.054
Because, okay, there is the physical
avocado that you might cut open,

00:42:04.355 --> 00:42:07.892
but then you're buying the time
it spent in a refrigerated space.

00:42:07.892 --> 00:42:11.061
You're paying rent to those, owners
of refrigeration, transportation.

00:42:11.061 --> 00:42:13.264
You're buying the transportation, etc.

00:42:13.264 --> 00:42:16.834
it's interesting to think about any good
that you buy, period

00:42:16.834 --> 00:42:18.168
ahead of lettuce, etc..

00:42:18.168 --> 00:42:21.238
How little is the lettuce? Whatever.

00:42:21.238 --> 00:42:23.407
Even the lettuce means,
because there is labor

00:42:23.407 --> 00:42:25.109
that went into the planting of the lettuce

00:42:25.109 --> 00:42:27.211
and there is the land of the lettuce, etc.

00:42:27.211 --> 00:42:30.180
so the idea of what are you buying
when you're buying something?

00:42:30.247 --> 00:42:33.751
Often that include the packaging, but
often it's just never really clear at all

00:42:33.751 --> 00:42:36.053
what it is
except this bundle of goods and services.

00:42:36.053 --> 00:42:38.355
I'm buying an entire slice of the economy.

00:42:38.355 --> 00:42:40.024
You literally are okay,

